links.slidetitle: Let’s see what you know already!
links.displaytext: Let’s see what you know already!

links.slidetitle: If you notice mild symptoms of altitude sickness, it's fine to keep on climbing.
links.displaytext: If you notice mild symptoms of altitude sickness, it's fine to keep on climbing.

links.slidetitle: In severe cases of altitude sickness, fluid collects in the lungs and the brain swells.
links.displaytext: In severe cases of altitude sickness, fluid collects in the lungs and the brain swells.

links.slidetitle: The three types of altitude sickness are: Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS), High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE), and Hypertension (HBP).
links.displaytext: The three types of altitude sickness are: Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS), High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE), and Hypertension (HBP).

links.slidetitle: High Altitude is defined as 8,000 - 12,000 feet (2,438 - 3,658 meters) above sea level.
links.displaytext: High Altitude is defined as 8,000 - 12,000 feet (2,438 - 3,658 meters) above sea level.

links.slidetitle: The life threatning complication of altitude sickness caused by fluid retention in the brain is known as High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE).
links.displaytext: The life threatning complication of altitude sickness caused by fluid retention in the brain is known as High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE).
